1
00:00:00,060 --> 00:00:03,564
but I was with the firm when
your father used to carry you in here.

2
00:00:03,647 --> 00:00:05,440
- I know.
- Your father came to me

3
00:00:05,441 --> 00:00:09,069
the day you were born and asked me
what I thought of the name Howard.

4
00:00:09,194 --> 00:00:13,115
I appreciate that, Willy,
but there just is no spot here for you.

5
00:00:13,240 --> 00:00:17,286
If I had a spot I would slam you
right in there, but I just don't.

6
00:00:17,369 --> 00:00:21,290
- All I need is 50 dollars a week.
- Where am I gonna put you, kid?

7
00:00:21,415 --> 00:00:23,958
It's not a question
of whether I can sell, huh?

8
00:00:23,959 --> 00:00:27,880
No, but it's a business and
everybody's gotta pull his own weight.

9
00:00:27,963 --> 00:00:30,590
- Let me tell you a story.
- Business is business.

10
00:00:30,591 --> 00:00:34,677
This is definitely business.
Listen. You don't understand this.

11
00:00:34,678 --> 00:00:38,766
When I was a boy, 18, 19,
I was already on the road.

12
00:00:38,849 --> 00:00:42,394
There was a question in my mind
whether selling had a future for me.

13
00:00:42,519 --> 00:00:45,773
In those days
I had a yearning to go to Alaska.

14
00:00:45,856 --> 00:00:48,776
There were three gold strikes
in one month in Alaska.

15
00:00:48,901 --> 00:00:51,820
I felt like going out,
just for the ride, you might say.

16
00:00:51,945 --> 00:00:55,574
- You don't say?
- My father lived many years in Alaska.

17
00:00:55,699 --> 00:00:57,909
He was an adventurous man.

18
00:00:57,910 --> 00:01:00,996
We got quite a streak of self-reliance
in our family.

19
00:01:01,079 --> 00:01:04,333
I thought I'd go out with
my older brother, try to locate him,

20
00:01:04,416 --> 00:01:06,000
maybe settle in the North.

21
00:01:06,001 --> 00:01:09,270
I was almost decided to go...

22
00:01:10,589 --> 00:01:13,216
...when I met a salesman
in the Parker House.

23
00:01:13,217 --> 00:01:15,301
His name was Dave Singleman.

24
00:01:15,302 --> 00:01:19,765
He was 84 years old and
he'd drummed merchandise in 31 states.

25
00:01:19,848 --> 00:01:23,602
Old Dave would go up to his room,
put on his green velvet slippers,

26
00:01:24,561 --> 00:01:26,854
pick up the phone and call the buyers.

27
00:01:26,855 --> 00:01:30,526
Without ever leaving his room
at the age of 84,

28
00:01:30,651 --> 00:01:32,836
he made his living.

29
00:01:33,320 --> 00:01:37,741
When I saw that, I realised that selling
was the greatest career a man could want

30
00:01:37,783 --> 00:01:42,120
because what could be more satisfying
than to be able to go at the age of 84

31
00:01:42,204 --> 00:01:44,121
into 20 or 30 different cities

32
00:01:44,122 --> 00:01:46,666
and pick up a phone
and be remembered and loved

33
00:01:46,667 --> 00:01:49,477
and helped by many different people.

34
00:01:50,671 --> 00:01:53,256
You know, when he died...

35
00:01:53,257 --> 00:01:55,925
And by the way, he died
the death of a salesman,

36
00:01:55,926 --> 00:01:59,379
in his green velvet slippers
in the smoker of the New York,

37
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:02,014
New Haven and Hartford
going into Boston.

38
00:02:02,015 --> 00:02:05,902
When he died, hundreds of salesmen
and buyers were at his funeral.

39
00:02:07,145 --> 00:02:11,525
Things were sad on a lot of trains
for months after that.

40
00:02:13,994 --> 00:02:17,247
You see, in those days there was
personality in it, Howard.

41
00:02:17,489 --> 00:02:22,077
There was respect and comradeship and...

42
00:02:23,161 --> 00:02:26,464
...and gratitude.
Today it's all cut and dry.

43
00:02:26,665 --> 00:02:30,460
And there's no chance for bringing
friendship to bear or personality.

44
00:02:30,544 --> 00:02:32,503
You see what I mean.

45
00:02:32,504 --> 00:02:35,674
- They don't know me anymore.
- That's just the thing, Willy.

46
00:02:35,799 --> 00:02:38,217
If I had 40 dollars a week,
that's all I need.

47
00:02:38,218 --> 00:02:40,970
- I can't take blood from a stone.
- Howard!

48
00:02:40,971 --> 00:02:43,932
The year Al Smith was nominated
your father came to me...

49
00:02:43,974 --> 00:02:46,852
I'm talking about your father!

50
00:02:46,935 --> 00:02:49,395
There were promises made
across this desk!

51
00:02:49,396 --> 00:02:52,582
You mustnt tell me
that you got people to see!

52
00:02:53,483 --> 00:02:58,054
I put 34 years into this firm,
Howard! Now I can't pay my insurance!

53
00:02:58,155 --> 00:03:00,823
You can't eat the orange
and throw the peel away!

54
00:03:00,824 --> 00:03:03,509
A man is not a piece of fruit!

55
00:03:06,163 --> 00:03:08,514
Pay attention.

56
00:03:09,583 --> 00:03:12,685
No, your father...

57
00:03:13,086 --> 00:03:15,629
Howard...

58
00:03:15,630 --> 00:03:19,134
In 1928 I had a big year.

59
00:03:20,485 --> 00:03:23,154
I averaged 170 dollars a week.

60
00:03:23,155 --> 00:03:26,366
- You never averaged 170 dollars a week.
- No, no, no!

61
00:03:26,449 --> 00:03:31,913
I averaged 170 dollars a week
in the year 1928!

62
00:03:31,955 --> 00:03:34,331
And your father came to me, Howard,

63
00:03:34,332 --> 00:03:37,252
right across this desk,
put his hand on my shoulder...

64
00:03:37,335 --> 00:03:41,222
You have to excuse me, Willy!
I have got to see some people.

65
00:03:41,423 --> 00:03:44,867
Pull yourself together.
I'll be back in a little while.

66
00:03:49,514 --> 00:03:51,307
Ah, pull myself together!

67
00:03:51,308 --> 00:03:53,451
What did I say to him?

68
00:03:57,188 --> 00:03:59,415
Oh, my god.

69
00:04:00,650 --> 00:04:02,835
I was yelling at him.

70
00:04:04,487 --> 00:04:08,658
Frank, Frank, don't you remember
what you told me that time?

71
00:04:08,742 --> 00:04:10,784
You put your hand on my shoulder...

72
00:04:10,785 --> 00:04:13,704
The capital of Delaware...

73
00:04:13,705 --> 00:04:16,807
Oh, Howard!

74
00:04:17,375 --> 00:04:19,293
Howard!

75
00:04:19,294 --> 00:04:22,255
Howard, Howard, shut it off!

76
00:04:22,339 --> 00:04:24,089
Shut it off!

77
00:04:24,090 --> 00:04:27,052
- Look, Willy...
- I gotta get myself some coffee.

78
00:04:27,135 --> 00:04:29,303
- I'll get coffee.
- Willy, look...

79
00:04:29,304 --> 00:04:34,017
Look, Willy,
you can't go to Boston for us.

80
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:39,397
- Why can't I go?
- I don't want you to represent us.

81
00:04:41,775 --> 00:04:45,169
I've been meaning to tell you
for a long time now.

82
00:04:46,905 --> 00:04:51,534
- Howard, are you firing me?
- I think you need a good long rest.

83
00:04:51,618 --> 00:04:55,747
When you feel better come back
and we'll try to work something out.

84
00:04:55,830 --> 00:04:57,498
I gotta earn money, Howard.

85
00:04:57,499 --> 00:05:00,502
Where are your sons?
Wort your sons give you a hand?

86
00:05:00,543 --> 00:05:03,295
Oh, they're working on a very big deal.

87
00:05:03,296 --> 00:05:05,089
This is no time for false pride.

88
00:05:05,090 --> 00:05:07,549
Go to your sons
and tell them you're tired.

89
00:05:07,550 --> 00:05:09,510
You got two great boys there.

90
00:05:09,511 --> 00:05:11,804
- No question.
- That's that, huh?

91
00:05:11,805 --> 00:05:13,806
In the meantime. All right.

92
00:05:13,807 --> 00:05:16,600
I'll go to...
I'll go to Boston tomorrow.

93
00:05:16,601 --> 00:05:18,435
No!

94
00:05:18,436 --> 00:05:20,454
No.

95
00:05:21,690 --> 00:05:24,566
I can't throw myself on my kids.
I'm not a freeloader.

96
00:05:24,567 --> 00:05:27,319
- Kid, I am busy this morning.
- Let me go to Boston.

97
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:30,673
I have got a line
of people to see this morning.

98
00:05:38,540 --> 00:05:40,290
- Sit down. Sit.
- What?

99
00:05:40,291 --> 00:05:42,226
Oh.

100
00:05:48,967 --> 00:05:52,720
Take five minutes
and pull yourself together.

101
00:05:52,804 --> 00:05:56,433
And then go home, will you?

102
00:05:56,516 --> 00:05:58,784
I need the office.

103
00:06:01,896 --> 00:06:04,690
Whenever you can this week,
drop off the samples.

104
00:06:04,691 --> 00:06:08,570
You'll feel better, Willy,
and then come back. We'll talk.

105
00:06:11,614 --> 00:06:14,659
Pull yourself together, kid.
There's people outside.

106
00:06:27,881 --> 00:06:30,967
Oh, Ben!

107
00:06:32,427 --> 00:06:35,821
How did you do it, huh?

108
00:06:36,973 --> 00:06:39,099
What's the answer?

109
00:06:39,100 --> 00:06:41,643
Did you wind up the Alaska deal already?

110
00:06:41,644 --> 00:06:46,024
Doesrt take much time if you know what
you're doing. I wanted to say good-bye.

111
00:06:46,191 --> 00:06:48,483
- I gotta talk to you.
- I haven't the time.

112
00:06:48,484 --> 00:06:51,028
Nothing's working out.
I don't know what to do.

113
00:06:51,029 --> 00:06:54,991
I bought timberland in Alaska. I need
a man to look after things for me.

114
00:06:55,074 --> 00:06:56,658
God, timberland!

115
00:06:56,659 --> 00:06:59,161
Me and my boys and those grand outdoors!

116
00:06:59,162 --> 00:07:01,038
A new continent on your doorstep.

117
00:07:01,039 --> 00:07:05,210
Get out of these cities. They're full of
talk, time payments and courts of law.

118
00:07:05,293 --> 00:07:08,630
- You can fight for a fortune up there.
- Linda! Linda!

119
00:07:08,713 --> 00:07:10,589
- Linda.
- You're back.

120
00:07:10,590 --> 00:07:12,215
- I haven't much time.
- Wait.

121
00:07:12,216 --> 00:07:14,426
He's got a proposition for me in Alaska.

122
00:07:14,427 --> 00:07:17,513
- But you've got a job here.
- But in Alaska, kid, I could...

123
00:07:17,597 --> 00:07:20,516
- You are doing well enough.
- Enough for what, dear?

124
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:24,646
Don't say things like that to him.
Enough to be happy right here, now.

125
00:07:24,729 --> 00:07:28,858
Why must everyone conquer the world?
You're well-liked, the boys love you.

126
00:07:28,983 --> 00:07:32,570
The other day old man Wagner told him
he'll be a member of the firm.

127
00:07:32,654 --> 00:07:36,032
- Didn't he, Willy?
- I'm building something with this firm.

128
00:07:36,115 --> 00:07:38,993
If a man is building
he must be on the right track.

129
00:07:39,118 --> 00:07:43,331
- What are you building? Where is it?
- That's true, Linda, there's nothing.

130
00:07:43,456 --> 00:07:46,501
Why, there's a man 84 years old, Willy.

131
00:07:46,584 --> 00:07:48,543
That's right, Ben, that's right!

132
00:07:48,544 --> 00:07:51,547
When I look at that man
I say what's there to worry about?

133
00:07:51,589 --> 00:07:54,842
All he has to do is go into any city,
pick up a phone

134
00:07:54,926 --> 00:07:56,969
and he's making his living. Know why?

135
00:07:56,970 --> 00:07:59,137
- I gotta go.
- Oh, look at this boy.

136
00:07:59,138 --> 00:08:03,101
Without a penny to his name, three
great universities are begging for him.

137
00:08:03,184 --> 00:08:07,838
From there the sky's the limit! It's
not what you do, Ben, it's who you know!

138
00:08:07,939 --> 00:08:11,234
And a smile on your face.
It's contacts, Ben, contacts!

139
00:08:11,317 --> 00:08:15,655
The whole wealth of Alaska passing over
the lunch table of the Commodore Hotel.

140
00:08:15,780 --> 00:08:18,615
And that's the wonder,
the wonder of this country,

141
00:08:18,616 --> 00:08:23,037
that a man can end with diamonds
on the basis of being liked.

142
00:08:23,162 --> 00:08:26,332
That's why, when you get
on that field today, it's important,

143
00:08:26,416 --> 00:08:30,002
'cause thousands of people
will be rooting for you, loving you.

144
00:08:30,086 --> 00:08:34,173
When he walks into a business office,
his name will sound out like a bell,

145
00:08:34,257 --> 00:08:37,134
and all the doors will open to him.
I seen it, Ben.

146
00:08:37,135 --> 00:08:41,180
I seen it a thousand times. You can't
feel it in your hands, but it's there.

147
00:08:41,264 --> 00:08:43,515
- Good-bye.
- Don't you think I'm right?

148
00:08:43,516 --> 00:08:47,144
- I value your advice.
- A new continent at your doorstep.

149
00:08:47,545 --> 00:08:50,171
You could walk out rich.

150
00:08:50,172 --> 00:08:52,173
Rich!

151
00:08:52,174 --> 00:08:56,053
We're gonna do a hit, Ben, you hear me?
We're gonna do a hit!

152
00:08:56,095 --> 00:08:58,137
Gee, I was afraid you left already.

153
00:08:58,138 --> 00:08:59,973
- What time is it?
- Ten past one.

154
00:08:59,974 --> 00:09:03,269
Oh, come on everybody,
Ebbets Field, next stop.

155
00:09:03,352 --> 00:09:06,397
- Where's the pennants?
- Did you pack fresh underwear?

156
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:09,732
- I want to go. - I'm
carrying your helmet. - I am.

157
00:09:09,733 --> 00:09:12,610
You promised me.
How am I gonna get in the locker room?

158
00:09:12,611 --> 00:09:14,529
Let him carry the shoulder guards.

159
00:09:14,530 --> 00:09:17,491
Can I? I told everybody
I was gonna be in the locker room.

160
00:09:17,533 --> 00:09:20,369
- It's the Clubhouse.
- I meant the Clubhouse.

161
00:09:22,246 --> 00:09:25,124
- Let him carry the shoulder guards.
- Stay close to us.

162
00:09:25,207 --> 00:09:29,177
- Wave when Biff comes out on the
field! You set, boy? - Ready to go, Pop.

163
00:09:29,378 --> 00:09:32,213
- Every muscle is ready.
- You realise what this means.

164
00:09:32,214 --> 00:09:34,173
You're coming home this afternoon

165
00:09:34,174 --> 00:09:37,010
captain of the All-Scholastic
Championship Team

166
00:09:37,011 --> 00:09:40,681
- of the city of New York.
- That's right, Pop, and remember,

167
00:09:40,764 --> 00:09:43,976
when I take off my helmet,
that touchdowrs for you.

168
00:09:48,814 --> 00:09:51,734
Let's go over.
I got no room for you, Charley.

169
00:09:51,817 --> 00:09:53,484
- Room for what?
- In the car.

170
00:09:53,485 --> 00:09:56,070
Going for a ride?
I want to shoot some casino.

171
00:09:56,071 --> 00:09:58,114
Don't you realise what today is?

172
00:09:58,115 --> 00:10:01,660
Oh, he knows, Willy.
He's just kidding you.

173
00:10:01,744 --> 00:10:05,772
That's nothing to kid about. I'm
not kidding, Linda. What's going on?

174
00:10:05,873 --> 00:10:08,374
He is playing at Ebbets Field today.

175
00:10:08,375 --> 00:10:11,920
- Baseball in this weather?
- Don't talk to him. We're late.

176
00:10:12,004 --> 00:10:13,963
- Didn't you hear the news?
- What?

177
00:10:13,964 --> 00:10:17,051
Don't you listen to the radio?
Ebbets Field just blew up.

178
00:10:17,176 --> 00:10:19,260
You go to hell! Everybody in?

179
00:10:19,261 --> 00:10:21,179
Knock a homer, Biff.
Knock a homer!

180
00:10:21,180 --> 00:10:23,431
I don't think that was funny, Charley.

181
00:10:23,432 --> 00:10:26,685
Did you hear me, huh?
This is the greatest day in his life.

182
00:10:26,769 --> 00:10:28,227
When are you gonna grow up?

183
00:10:28,228 --> 00:10:30,813
When this game is over
you won't be laughing anymore.

184
00:10:30,814 --> 00:10:33,734
They'll be calling him
another Red Grange, 25,000 a year.

185
00:10:33,817 --> 00:10:35,193
- That so?
- Yeah!

186
00:10:35,194 --> 00:10:37,570
- Wait a minute, Willy. I'm sorry.
- Yeah?

187
00:10:37,571 --> 00:10:40,741
But tell me something.
Who is Red Grange?

188
00:10:40,824 --> 00:10:43,451
Put up your hands.
Put up your hands, come on.

189
00:10:43,452 --> 00:10:46,997
Put up your hands. Who do you think
you are, better than everybody?

190
00:10:47,081 --> 00:10:49,958
Put up your hands! Put up your hands!

191
00:10:50,042 --> 00:10:52,878
Put up your hands.
Who the hell do you think you are?

192
00:10:53,003 --> 00:10:56,799
You don't know everything,
you big ignorant stupid...

193
00:10:56,882 --> 00:10:59,760
Put up your hands.
What are you walking away for?

194
00:10:59,843 --> 00:11:03,514
Don't walk away. You gonna say
something to me, say it to my face.

195
00:11:03,797 --> 00:11:05,881
I know you laugh at me behind my back.

196
00:11:05,882 --> 00:11:09,303
You'll be laughing out of the other
side of your face after this game.

197
00:11:09,386 --> 00:11:12,347
The woods are burning.
Touchdown! Touchdown!

198
00:11:12,431 --> 00:11:16,685
Eighty thousand people!
Right between the goal posts.

199
00:11:16,768 --> 00:11:19,938
Touchdown! Touchdown!

200
00:11:20,022 --> 00:11:23,191
Hello, baby! Touchdown!

201
00:11:23,275 --> 00:11:25,526
Touchdown! Ah, Jenny.

202
00:11:25,527 --> 00:11:28,713
Jenny, good to see you.
How are you?

203
00:11:29,072 --> 00:11:32,200
- Working? Or still honest?
- Fine.

204
00:11:32,284 --> 00:11:35,162
- How you been feeling?
- Not much any more.

205
00:11:36,246 --> 00:11:38,640
- Oh!
- Hello, Uncle Willy.

206
00:11:41,209 --> 00:11:43,353
Bernard.

207
00:11:44,087 --> 00:11:46,547
- Look who's here.
- How are you?

208
00:11:46,548 --> 00:11:49,509
- What are you doing here?
- I just stopped by to see Pop.

209
00:11:49,593 --> 00:11:53,096
To get off my feet till my train leaves.
I'm going to Washington.

210
00:11:53,180 --> 00:11:55,556
- Is he in?
- He's with the accountant.

211
00:11:55,557 --> 00:11:59,193
Sit down. What are you
gonna do in Washington?

212
00:11:59,394 --> 00:12:03,614
- Just a case I've got there.
- That so? You gonna play tennis there?

213
00:12:03,815 --> 00:12:06,275
I'm staying with a friend
who's got a court.

214
00:12:06,276 --> 00:12:09,153
You don't say.
Their own tennis court?

215
00:12:09,154 --> 00:12:11,990
- Those are fine people, I bet.
- They're very nice.

216
00:12:12,074 --> 00:12:14,158
- Dad tells me Biff's in town.
- Yeah.

217
00:12:14,159 --> 00:12:17,579
Biff's in. He's working
on a very big deal, Bernard.

218
00:12:17,704 --> 00:12:21,857
- What's Biff doing? - He's been
doing very big things in the West,

219
00:12:21,958 --> 00:12:24,668
but he decided
to establish himself here.

220
00:12:24,669 --> 00:12:27,605
Very big. We're having dinner.

221
00:12:28,957 --> 00:12:31,834
Did I hear your wife had a boy?

222
00:12:31,835 --> 00:12:34,545
That's right. Our second.

223
00:12:34,546 --> 00:12:36,689
Two boys.

224
00:12:37,257 --> 00:12:40,260
- What do you know?
- You still with the old firm, Willy?

225
00:12:41,511 --> 00:12:46,725
I'm overjoyed to see how
you made the grade, Bernard, overjoyed.

226
00:12:46,808 --> 00:12:49,143
It's an encouraging thing to see.

227
00:12:49,144 --> 00:12:54,533
A young man really... really...

228
00:12:54,917 --> 00:12:59,103
Ah, it looks very good for Biff.
Very good.

229
00:13:07,078 --> 00:13:12,033
- Bernard. - What is it, Willy?
- What... What's the secret?

230
00:13:12,217 --> 00:13:14,260
- What secret?
- How did you...?

231
00:13:14,261 --> 00:13:17,347
- Why didn't he ever catch on?
- Willy, I wouldn't know that.

232
00:13:17,430 --> 00:13:20,182
Oh, you were his friend,
his boyhood friend.

233
00:13:20,183 --> 00:13:22,268
It's something I don't understand.

234
00:13:22,269 --> 00:13:24,895
His life ended
after that Ebbets Field game.

235
00:13:24,896 --> 00:13:27,773
From the age of 17
nothing good ever happened to him.

236
00:13:27,774 --> 00:13:32,279
- He never trained himself for anything.
- He took correspondence courses.

237
00:13:32,320 --> 00:13:36,074
Radio mechanics, television...
He never made the slightest mark.

238
00:13:36,157 --> 00:13:38,659
- Do you want to talk candidly?
- Bernard.

239
00:13:38,660 --> 00:13:42,873
I regard you as a very brilliant man.
Bernard, I value your advice.

240
00:13:42,956 --> 00:13:45,541
The hell with advice.
I couldn't advise you.

241
00:13:45,542 --> 00:13:48,335
There's one thing
I have always wanted to ask you.

242
00:13:48,336 --> 00:13:51,673
When he was supposed to graduate
and the teacher flunked him...

243
00:13:51,756 --> 00:13:53,173
Ruined his life.

244
00:13:53,174 --> 00:13:56,428
All he had to do was go
to summer school, make up that subject.

245
00:13:56,511 --> 00:13:59,681
- That's right. That's right!
- Did you tell him not to go?

246
00:13:59,764 --> 00:14:02,600
Me? I begged him to go.
I ordered him to go.

247
00:14:02,601 --> 00:14:05,227
- Why wouldn't he go?
- Why? Why, Bernard!

248
00:14:05,228 --> 00:14:08,481
That questiors been trailing me
like a ghost for 15 years.

249
00:14:08,565 --> 00:14:13,253
He flunked the subject and he laid down
and died like a hammer hit him.

250
00:14:13,578 --> 00:14:16,330
Let me talk to you, Bernard.
I got nobody to talk to.

251
00:14:16,331 --> 00:14:20,610
It wasn't my fault. It keeps going
around in my head, maybe I did something.

252
00:14:20,794 --> 00:14:22,253
I got nothing to give him.

253
00:14:22,254 --> 00:14:23,671
Don't take it so hard.

254
00:14:23,672 --> 00:14:26,149
Why did he lay down?

255
00:14:27,467 --> 00:14:29,552
- What is the story there?
- Willy...

256
00:14:29,553 --> 00:14:31,554
You're his friend. Come on.

257
00:14:31,555 --> 00:14:35,642
Willy, I remember it was June.
Our grades came out. He'd flunked math.

258
00:14:35,725 --> 00:14:38,102
That son of a bitch ruined his life.

259
00:14:38,103 --> 00:14:42,190
Then Biff just got very angry and
he was ready to enrol in summer school.

260
00:14:42,274 --> 00:14:44,650
- He was?
- He wasn't beaten by it at all.

261
00:14:44,651 --> 00:14:47,486
But then, Willy, see...

262
00:14:47,487 --> 00:14:49,113
What?

263
00:14:49,114 --> 00:14:51,907
He disappeared from the block
for almost a month.

264
00:14:51,908 --> 00:14:55,328
I got the idea that he'd gone
up to New England to see you.

265
00:14:55,412 --> 00:14:58,415
Did he ever talk with you then?

266
00:14:58,498 --> 00:15:01,208
- Willy?
- Yeah.

267
00:15:01,209 --> 00:15:03,686
Yeah.

268
00:15:04,796 --> 00:15:07,131
He came to Boston.
What about it?

269
00:15:07,132 --> 00:15:10,677
Well, it's just
that when he came back...

270
00:15:13,096 --> 00:15:15,598
I'll never forget this.

271
00:15:15,599 --> 00:15:18,977
It always mystifies me
because I thought so well of Biff.

272
00:15:19,060 --> 00:15:21,621
I loved him, Willy, you know.

273
00:15:21,855 --> 00:15:24,732
He came back after that month
and took his sneakers.

274
00:15:24,733 --> 00:15:29,279
Remember those sneakers with the
University of Virginia on them?

275
00:15:29,362 --> 00:15:32,590
He was so proud of them.
Wore them every day.

276
00:15:33,116 --> 00:15:36,661
He took them down into the cellar,
burned them up in the furnace.

277
00:15:36,745 --> 00:15:39,263
We had a fistfight.

278
00:15:39,497 --> 00:15:42,333
It lasted at least half an hour,
just the two of us,

279
00:15:42,334 --> 00:15:46,504
punching each other down in the cellar,
crying right through it.

280
00:15:46,588 --> 00:15:50,300
I often thought how strange it was
that I knew he'd given up his life.

281
00:15:54,638 --> 00:15:57,365
What happened in Boston, Willy?

282
00:15:58,350 --> 00:16:01,186
I just bring it up because you asked me.

283
00:16:01,269 --> 00:16:03,354
What's that got to do with it?

284
00:16:03,355 --> 00:16:06,858
- Don't get sore.
- What are you trying to do, blame me?

285
00:16:06,942 --> 00:16:09,568
If a boy lays down is that my fault?

286
00:16:09,569 --> 00:16:12,697
- Don't take it...
- Don't you talk to me that way.

287
00:16:12,781 --> 00:16:15,199
What does that mean,
huh, what happened?

288
00:16:15,300 --> 00:16:18,361
Hey!

289
00:16:22,307 --> 00:16:25,143
- You're gonna miss that train.
- Yeah, I'm going.

290
00:16:31,149 --> 00:16:33,108
Good-bye, Willy.

291
00:16:33,109 --> 00:16:37,864
- Don't worry about it. If at first you
don't succeed... - Yes, I believe in that.

292
00:16:37,947 --> 00:16:41,242
Sometimes, Willy, it's better for a man
just to walk away.

293
00:16:41,367 --> 00:16:43,744
- Walk away?
- That's right.

294
00:16:43,745 --> 00:16:46,555
What if you can't walk away?

295
00:16:47,123 --> 00:16:50,400
I guess that's when it's tough.

296
00:16:51,586 --> 00:16:53,479
Good-bye, Willy.

297
00:16:57,425 --> 00:16:59,259
Good-bye, boy.

298
00:16:59,260 --> 00:17:03,097
How do you like this kid?
Gonna argue a case in the Supreme Court.

299
00:17:03,181 --> 00:17:06,033
- Pop!
- No.

300
00:17:06,601 --> 00:17:08,977
- The Supreme Court?
- I gotta run.

301
00:17:08,978 --> 00:17:11,747
- Bye, Dad.
- Knock 'em dead, Bernard.

302
00:17:15,693 --> 00:17:18,529
The Supreme Court.

303
00:17:18,822 --> 00:17:20,572
And he didn't even mention it?

304
00:17:20,573 --> 00:17:23,634
He don't have to.
He's gonna do it.

305
00:17:24,244 --> 00:17:28,456
And you never told him what to do.
You never took any interest in him.

306
00:17:28,540 --> 00:17:31,751
My salvation is that I never
took any interest in anything.

307
00:17:31,834 --> 00:17:36,781
Here's some money, 50 dollars.
I got an accountant inside.

308
00:17:37,549 --> 00:17:40,109
Uh, Charley, look, uh...

309
00:17:40,593 --> 00:17:45,265
I got my insurance to pay.
If you could manage it, I...

310
00:17:46,808 --> 00:17:49,643
I need 110 dollars.

311
00:17:49,644 --> 00:17:52,730
- I'd draw from my bank, but...
- Sit down, Willy.

312
00:17:52,855 --> 00:17:55,357
I'm keeping an account of everything.

313
00:17:55,358 --> 00:17:57,943
- Listen to me.
- I'll pay every penny back.

314
00:17:57,944 --> 00:18:01,781
- I want you to know I appreciate...
- What's going on inside your head?

315
00:18:01,864 --> 00:18:04,491
- Why? I'm simply...
- I offered you a job.

316
00:18:04,492 --> 00:18:07,870
You can make 50 dollars a week
and I won't send you on the road.

317
00:18:07,954 --> 00:18:10,306
- I got a job.
- Without pay?

318
00:18:11,040 --> 00:18:14,310
What kind of a job is a job without pay?

319
00:18:16,629 --> 00:18:19,339
Now, look, kid. Enough is enough.

320
00:18:19,340 --> 00:18:22,176
I'm no genius, but I know
when I'm being insulted.

321
00:18:22,260 --> 00:18:24,803
- Insulted?
- Why don't you want to work for me?

322
00:18:24,804 --> 00:18:27,014
What does it matter with you?
I got a job.

323
00:18:27,015 --> 00:18:30,242
What do you walk in here every week for?

324
00:18:33,730 --> 00:18:38,693
Well, if... if you don't
want me to walk in here...

325
00:18:38,818 --> 00:18:41,946
- I am offering you a job.
- I don't want your job.

326
00:18:42,030 --> 00:18:45,115
When the hell are you gonna grow up?

327
00:18:45,575 --> 00:18:49,161
You big ignoramus! If you say
that to me again I'll rap you one.

328
00:18:49,162 --> 00:18:52,440
I don't care how big...
...how big you are.

329
00:19:02,216 --> 00:19:06,846
- How much do you need, Willy?
- Ah, Charley, I'm strapped.

330
00:19:07,013 --> 00:19:10,883
I'm strapped. I don't know
what to do. I was just fired.

331
00:19:11,184 --> 00:19:14,912
- Howard fired you?
- That's not no...

332
00:19:16,114 --> 00:19:20,642
Imagine that. I named him Howard.
I named him! I named him Howard!

333
00:19:20,943 --> 00:19:24,947
Willy, when are you gonna realise
that them things don't mean anything?

334
00:19:25,031 --> 00:19:28,092
You named him Howard
but you can't sell that.

335
00:19:28,201 --> 00:19:31,245
The only thing you got in this
world is what you can sell.

336
00:19:31,370 --> 00:19:35,124
The funny thing is, you're a salesman
and you don't know that.

337
00:19:35,208 --> 00:19:38,711
I always try to think otherwise,
I guess. I always felt...

338
00:19:40,838 --> 00:19:44,008
...if a man was impressive
and well-liked then nothing...

339
00:19:44,092 --> 00:19:46,969
Why must everybody like you?
Who liked JP Morgan?

340
00:19:47,053 --> 00:19:50,515
Was he impressive? In a Turkish bath
he looked like a butcher.

341
00:19:50,598 --> 00:19:54,894
With his pockets on
he was very well-liked.

342
00:20:00,274 --> 00:20:05,112
Now, listen, Willy,
I know you don't like me.

343
00:20:05,196 --> 00:20:08,366
And nobody can say I'm in love with you.

344
00:20:09,909 --> 00:20:13,538
But I'll give you a job
just for the hell of it.

345
00:20:14,121 --> 00:20:18,743
- What do you say?
- No. No, I just...

346
00:20:19,126 --> 00:20:21,503
No, I just can't work for you, Charley.

347
00:20:21,504 --> 00:20:23,505
- What are you, jealous of me?
- No!

348
00:20:23,506 --> 00:20:26,258
I can't work for you, that's all.
Don't ask me why.

349
00:20:26,259 --> 00:20:29,903
You've been jealous of me
all your life, you damn fool.

350
00:20:31,973 --> 00:20:34,241
Here.

351
00:20:35,810 --> 00:20:38,688
- Pay your insurance.
- I'm keeping strict accounts.

352
00:20:38,771 --> 00:20:43,742
I got some work to do. Take care
of yourself. And pay your insurance!

353
00:20:50,333 --> 00:20:55,296
It's funny, after all the highways
and the trains and the appointments

354
00:20:55,380 --> 00:20:57,773
and the years...

355
00:20:59,759 --> 00:21:02,903
...you end up worth
more dead than alive.

356
00:21:06,057 --> 00:21:09,268
Willy, nobody's worth nothing dead.

357
00:21:14,524 --> 00:21:16,750
You hear what I said?

358
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:20,963
Willy!

359
00:21:21,614 --> 00:21:25,852
Oh, apologise to Bernard for me
when you see him.

360
00:21:26,035 --> 00:21:28,912
I didn't mean to argue with him.
He's a fine boy.

361
00:21:28,913 --> 00:21:34,794
They're all fine boys. And they'll
end up big, all of them someday.

362
00:21:35,753 --> 00:21:37,879
They'll all play tennis together.

363
00:21:37,880 --> 00:21:40,967
Wish me luck, Charley.
He saw Bill Oliver today.

364
00:21:42,350 --> 00:21:44,870
Good luck.

365
00:21:45,012 --> 00:21:48,506
Oh, Charley,
you're the only friend I got.

366
00:21:54,863 --> 00:21:58,066
Isn't that a remarkable thing?

367
00:22:06,609 --> 00:22:08,585
Jesus.

368
00:22:13,783 --> 00:22:16,459
In the front
you're in the middle of noise.

369
00:22:16,460 --> 00:22:20,156
Whenever you've got a party, Mr. Loman,
tell me, I'll put you back here.

370
00:22:20,381 --> 00:22:23,300
You look French.
How's it coming, Stanley?

371
00:22:23,301 --> 00:22:27,597
It's a dog's life. I only wish that
during the war they took me in the Army.

372
00:22:27,680 --> 00:22:30,641
- I could have been dead.
- You got lobsters?

373
00:22:30,725 --> 00:22:34,986
- A hundred percent big. - With the claws.
- Don't worry, I don't give you no mice.

374
00:22:35,187 --> 00:22:37,731
How about some wine?
Put a hat on the meal.

375
00:22:37,732 --> 00:22:41,444
No, the recipe I brought you from
overseas with the champagne in it

376
00:22:41,611 --> 00:22:45,239
I still got that in the kitchen,
but it'll cost you a buck a piece.

377
00:22:45,323 --> 00:22:47,699
- That's all right.
- You hit a number?

378
00:22:47,700 --> 00:22:50,201
My brother, I think
he pulled off a deal today.

379
00:22:50,202 --> 00:22:53,998
- I think we're going into business.
- That's the best, family business.

380
00:22:54,123 --> 00:22:56,333
- That's the best.
- That's what I think.

381
00:22:56,334 --> 00:22:59,712
What's the difference?
Somebody steals, it's in the family.

382
00:22:59,795 --> 00:23:02,648
Shh. Strudel.

383
00:23:03,466 --> 00:23:07,303
- Ma'am?
- I'm expecting someone.

384
00:23:09,430 --> 00:23:14,018
Oh, look at that mouth. Oh, God,
and the binoculars. Wait on her.

385
00:23:15,478 --> 00:23:17,979
- Would you like a menu?
- I'd like a...

386
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:20,273
Why don't you bring her...
Do you mind?

387
00:23:20,274 --> 00:23:24,111
I sell champagne and I'd like her
to try my brand. Bring her a champagne.

388
00:23:24,195 --> 00:23:27,406
- That's awfully nice of you.
- It's all company money.

389
00:23:27,490 --> 00:23:30,325
That's a charming product
to be selling, isn't it?

390
00:23:30,326 --> 00:23:32,827
Like everything else,
selling is selling.

391
00:23:32,828 --> 00:23:36,715
- I suppose? - You don't happen
to sell? - No, I don't sell.

392
00:23:36,916 --> 00:23:40,294
Would you object to a compliment?
You ought to be on a magazine cover.

393
00:23:40,578 --> 00:23:44,990
- I have been. -W hat did I say before?
See, Stanley, she's a cover girl.

394
00:23:45,091 --> 00:23:47,884
- Oh, I could see, I could see.
- What magazine?

395
00:23:47,885 --> 00:23:49,844
A lot of them.
Thank you.

396
00:23:49,845 --> 00:23:51,930
You know what they say in France?

397
00:23:51,931 --> 00:23:54,265
Champagne is the drink
of the complexion.

398
00:23:54,266 --> 00:23:57,269
- Hiya, Biffo.
- Sorry I'm late.

399
00:23:57,353 --> 00:24:00,630
- No. No, no, I just got here.
Miss, um...? - Forsythe.

400
00:24:00,731 --> 00:24:03,483
Miss Forsythe, this is my brother.

401
00:24:03,784 --> 00:24:05,844
Is Dad here?

402
00:24:06,745 --> 00:24:10,290
You might have heard of him.
He's a great football player.

403
00:24:10,374 --> 00:24:13,335
- Really? What team?
- You're familiar with football?

404
00:24:13,419 --> 00:24:16,296
- I'm afraid I'm not.
- Biff's with the New York Giants.

405
00:24:16,380 --> 00:24:18,673
- Well, it is nice, isn't it?
- Good health.

406
00:24:18,674 --> 00:24:20,633
- Happy to meet you.
- That's my name.

407
00:24:20,634 --> 00:24:23,386
It's Harold, but at West Point
they called me Happy.

408
00:24:23,387 --> 00:24:24,971
I see. How do you do?

409
00:24:24,972 --> 00:24:27,615
- Isn't Dad coming?
- You want her?

410
00:24:29,685 --> 00:24:32,812
- What? - You want her?
- I could never make that.

411
00:24:32,813 --> 00:24:36,442
I remember the time that idea
would never come into your head.

412
00:24:36,525 --> 00:24:40,245
- I just saw... - Wait, please. I've
got to see the old confidence.

413
00:24:40,446 --> 00:24:43,824
If you want her she's on call.
I'm telling you, watch this.

414
00:24:45,059 --> 00:24:48,062
Honey, are you busy?

415
00:24:48,145 --> 00:24:50,897
Well, I am
but I could make a phone call.

416
00:24:50,898 --> 00:24:54,234
Go and do that, will you, honey,
and see if you can get a friend.

417
00:24:54,318 --> 00:24:58,113
We'll be here for awhile. Biff,
one of the greatest football players.

418
00:24:58,238 --> 00:25:01,075
- I'm certainly happy to meet you.
- Come back soon.

419
00:25:01,358 --> 00:25:05,579
- I'll try.
- Don't try, honey. Try hard.

420
00:25:07,915 --> 00:25:10,876
Isn't that a shame?
Beautiful girl like that.

421
00:25:10,959 --> 00:25:13,795
- That's why I can't get married.
- Hap, look...

422
00:25:13,796 --> 00:25:15,880
- I told you she's on call.
- Cut it out.

423
00:25:15,881 --> 00:25:18,257
I want to say something.

424
00:25:18,258 --> 00:25:20,635
- Did you see Oliver?
- I saw him, all right.

425
00:25:20,636 --> 00:25:23,555
I want to tell Dad a couple of things.
I want you to help.

426
00:25:23,680 --> 00:25:26,767
- Is he gonna back you?
- Are you crazy?

427
00:25:26,850 --> 00:25:29,268
You're out of your head,
do you know that?

428
00:25:29,269 --> 00:25:30,645
Why, what happened?

429
00:25:30,646 --> 00:25:33,106
I did a terrible thing today, Hap.

430
00:25:33,107 --> 00:25:36,652
It's been the strangest day
I ever went through.

431
00:25:36,735 --> 00:25:39,320
- I'm a little numb.
- What, he wouldn't see you?

432
00:25:39,321 --> 00:25:43,374
I waited six hours for him, see.
All day I kept sending my name in.

433
00:25:43,575 --> 00:25:47,329
Even tried to date his secretary
so she got me through. Not so.

434
00:25:47,454 --> 00:25:50,791
You're not showing the confidence.
But he remembered you?

435
00:25:50,874 --> 00:25:55,504
Finally at 5:00 he comes out,
didn't remember who I was or anything.

436
00:25:55,587 --> 00:25:58,339
Biff, did you tell him my Florida idea?

437
00:25:58,340 --> 00:26:01,050
Hap, he walked away.

438
00:26:01,051 --> 00:26:04,930
I saw him and for one minute I got
so mad I could have torn the walls down.

439
00:26:05,013 --> 00:26:08,851
How the hell did I ever get the idea
that I was a salesman there?

440
00:26:08,934 --> 00:26:11,727
I believed myself
that I'd been a salesman for him.

441
00:26:11,728 --> 00:26:16,441
Then he gave me one look and I realised
what a ridiculous lie my life's been.

442
00:26:16,525 --> 00:26:19,836
We have been talking in a dream
for 15 years.

443
00:26:20,154 --> 00:26:23,164
- I was a shipping clerk.
- What did you do?

444
00:26:23,365 --> 00:26:26,493
Well, he... he left, see.

445
00:26:26,577 --> 00:26:30,372
His secretary went out
and I was alone in the waiting room.

446
00:26:31,623 --> 00:26:35,210
And next thing I know,
I was in his office.

447
00:26:35,294 --> 00:26:39,089
Panel walls and everything.

448
00:26:39,172 --> 00:26:43,677
I can't explain it, Hap.
I took his fountain pen.

449
00:26:43,760 --> 00:26:45,845
Geez. Did he catch you?

450
00:26:45,846 --> 00:26:50,058
I ran out. I ran down all 11 flights.
I ran and ran and ran.

451
00:26:50,142 --> 00:26:52,852
Boy, that was dumb, Biff.
Why did you do that?

452
00:26:52,853 --> 00:26:54,645
I don't know.

453
00:26:54,646 --> 00:26:57,499
I just wanted to take something.

454
00:27:00,319 --> 00:27:02,862
You gotta help me, Hap.
I want to tell Pop.

455
00:27:02,863 --> 00:27:04,923
Are you crazy? What for?

456
00:27:07,743 --> 00:27:12,122
He's gotta understand I'm not the man
somebody lends that kind of money to.

457
00:27:12,205 --> 00:27:14,957
He thinks I've been spiting him
all these years.

458
00:27:14,958 --> 00:27:18,170
Tell him something nice.
Say you got a date with Oliver tomorrow.

459
00:27:18,253 --> 00:27:21,340
- What do I do tomorrow?
- Dad is never so happy

460
00:27:21,423 --> 00:27:24,526
as when he's
looking forward to something.

461
00:27:26,261 --> 00:27:28,721
Gee, I haven't been here in years!

462
00:27:28,722 --> 00:27:31,600
- Sit down. You want a drink?
- Sure, I don't mind.

463
00:27:31,683 --> 00:27:33,768
- You look worried.
- No.

464
00:27:33,769 --> 00:27:36,103
Uh, Scotch all around.
Make it doubles.

465
00:27:36,104 --> 00:27:39,566
You had a couple already, didn't you?
Did everything go all right?

466
00:27:39,650 --> 00:27:42,903
- I had an experience today, Pop.
- That so? What happened?

467
00:27:42,986 --> 00:27:45,738
I wanted to tell you everything
from first to last.

468
00:27:45,739 --> 00:27:48,616
It's been a strange day.
I had to wait quite a while.

469
00:27:48,617 --> 00:27:50,076
- Oliver?
- Yeah, Oliver.

470
00:27:50,077 --> 00:27:52,119
All day, as a matter of cold fact.

471
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:57,167
And a lot of instances, Pop,
facts about my life came back to me.

472
00:27:57,250 --> 00:28:00,712
Who was it, Pop, whoever said
I was a salesman with Oliver?

473
00:28:00,837 --> 00:28:03,715
- Well, you were.
- No, I was a shipping clerk, Dad.

474
00:28:03,799 --> 00:28:06,968
I don't know who said it first
but I was never a salesman for Oliver.

475
00:28:07,052 --> 00:28:09,887
- What are you talking about?
- Hold onto the facts.

476
00:28:09,888 --> 00:28:12,223
I was a shipping clerk.

477
00:28:12,224 --> 00:28:14,266
- Listen to me...
- Dad, let me finish.

478
00:28:14,267 --> 00:28:16,894
I'm not interested in stories
about the past.

479
00:28:16,895 --> 00:28:18,687
The woods are burning, boys.

480
00:28:18,688 --> 00:28:21,399
There's a big blaze going on all around.

481
00:28:21,400 --> 00:28:22,983
I was fired today.

482
00:28:22,984 --> 00:28:24,735
How could you be?

483
00:28:24,736 --> 00:28:28,949
And I'm looking for a little good news
to tell your mother

484
00:28:29,074 --> 00:28:31,409
- because the woman has suffered.
- Dad!

485
00:28:31,410 --> 00:28:35,247
I haven't got a story left in my head
so don't give me a lecture about facts.

486
00:28:35,372 --> 00:28:38,458
I am not interested.
Now, what have you got to say to me?

487
00:28:38,542 --> 00:28:41,811
Did you see Oliver, huh?

488
00:28:42,045 --> 00:28:44,588
- Geez, Dad.
- You didn't go up there?

489
00:28:44,589 --> 00:28:47,801
- Sure, he went up there.
- I saw him. How could they fire you?

490
00:28:47,884 --> 00:28:51,513
- What kind of welcome did he give you?
- He won't let you work on commission?

491
00:28:51,596 --> 00:28:54,306
- I'm out! He gave you a warm welcome?
- Sure, Pop.

492
00:28:54,307 --> 00:28:57,936
I was wondering if he'd remember you.
A man doesn't see him in ten years,

493
00:28:58,019 --> 00:29:00,855
he gives him a welcome.
You know why he remembered?

494
00:29:00,856 --> 00:29:05,110
- You impressed him in those days.
- Dad, can we talk and get this down?

495
00:29:05,193 --> 00:29:09,072
What happened? Did he take you in
his office or talk in the waiting room?

496
00:29:09,156 --> 00:29:11,866
- He came in...
- I bet he threw his arms around you.

497
00:29:11,867 --> 00:29:15,036
- He's a fine man, a hard man to see.
- Oh, I know that.

498
00:29:15,162 --> 00:29:17,413
- Is that where you had the drinks?
- Yeah.

499
00:29:17,414 --> 00:29:20,040
- He told him my Florida idea.
- Don't interrupt.

500
00:29:20,041 --> 00:29:23,295
- How'd he react to the Florida idea?
- Give me a minute to explain.

501
00:29:23,378 --> 00:29:27,424
I've been waiting for you to explain
since I sat down here. What happened?

502
00:29:27,507 --> 00:29:30,802
- I talked, he listened to me.
- Oh, the way he listens.

503
00:29:30,886 --> 00:29:33,304
- What was his answer?
- An... Answer...

504
00:29:33,305 --> 00:29:36,224
You're not letting me tell you
what I want to tell you.

505
00:29:36,308 --> 00:29:37,933
- You didn't see him.
- I did.

506
00:29:37,934 --> 00:29:41,188
- You insult him or something?
- Dad! Will you let me out of it?

507
00:29:41,313 --> 00:29:43,898
- Will you just let me out of it?
- What happened?

508
00:29:43,899 --> 00:29:45,774
- I can't talk to him.
- Tell him.

509
00:29:45,775 --> 00:29:49,362
- Shut up and leave me alone.
- No, no. You had to go and flunk math.

510
00:29:49,487 --> 00:29:52,574
- Dad, what are you talking about?
- Math, math, math.

511
00:29:52,657 --> 00:29:56,119
- Take it easy, Pop.
- If you hadrt of flunked you'd be set.

512
00:29:56,203 --> 00:29:59,289
I'm gonna tell you what happened
and you're gonna listen to me.

513
00:29:59,372 --> 00:30:03,376
I waited six hours and I kept sending
my name in but he wouldn't see me.

514
00:30:03,460 --> 00:30:06,379
- Finally he came.
- Biff flunked mathl

515
00:30:06,463 --> 00:30:09,131
- They won't graduate him.
- Where is he?

516
00:30:09,132 --> 00:30:11,216
He ran off.
He went to Grand Central.

517
00:30:11,217 --> 00:30:12,968
Is Uncle Willy in Boston?

518
00:30:12,969 --> 00:30:16,473
See, so I'm washed up with Oliver,
Pop, do you understand that?

519
00:30:16,556 --> 00:30:19,433
- Are you listening?
- If you hadrt have flunked...

520
00:30:19,434 --> 00:30:23,229
- Dad, what are you talking about?
- I didn't flunk math. What pen?

521
00:30:23,313 --> 00:30:26,148
- That was dumb, Biff.
- You took Oliver's pen.

522
00:30:26,149 --> 00:30:29,444
- I just explained it.
- You stole Bill Oliver's fountain pen.

523
00:30:29,527 --> 00:30:32,404
I didn't exactly steal it.
I was trying to tell you.

524
00:30:32,405 --> 00:30:35,408
He had it in his hand,
Oliver walked in, he got nervous.

525
00:30:35,492 --> 00:30:38,243
- My god, Biff.
- I never intended to do it...

526
00:30:38,244 --> 00:30:41,706
- I'm not in my room. I'm not there.
- Ringing Mr Loman.

527
00:30:41,790 --> 00:30:44,041
- Now, stop it.
- Mr Loman does not answer.

528
00:30:44,042 --> 00:30:45,960
- I'm not there.
- Shall I page him?

529
00:30:45,961 --> 00:30:48,754
- You're no good, no good for anything.
- I am, Dad.

530
00:30:48,755 --> 00:30:51,340
I'll find something.
Don't worry about anything.

531
00:30:51,341 --> 00:30:53,133
- Talk to me.
- Paging Mr Loman.

532
00:30:53,134 --> 00:30:55,719
- No! No!
- He'll strike something, Pop, please.

533
00:30:55,720 --> 00:30:58,347
- No!
- Dad, I'm telling you something good.

534
00:30:58,348 --> 00:31:01,893
Oliver talked to his partner
about the Florida idea.

535
00:31:02,018 --> 00:31:03,977
- You listening, Dad? Dad?
- Yeah.

536
00:31:03,978 --> 00:31:08,233
He talked to his partner and he came
to me and I'm gonna be all right, Pop.

537
00:31:08,316 --> 00:31:10,567
He said it's just a question
of the amount.

538
00:31:10,568 --> 00:31:14,197
- Then you... Then you got it?
- It's gonna be terrific, Pop.

539
00:31:14,322 --> 00:31:16,740
Aw, then you got it, haven't you?

540
00:31:16,741 --> 00:31:19,661
- You got it, haven't you? You got it!
- No.

541
00:31:19,744 --> 00:31:22,329
I'm supposed to have lunch
with him tomorrow.

542
00:31:22,330 --> 00:31:25,291
I'm telling you so you'll know
I can make an impression.

543
00:31:25,375 --> 00:31:28,753
I'll make good somewheres,
but I can't go tomorrow.

544
00:31:28,837 --> 00:31:30,963
- Why not? You simply...
- The pen, Pop.

545
00:31:30,964 --> 00:31:33,716
You give him the pen,
tell him it was an oversight.

546
00:31:33,717 --> 00:31:35,259
- You have lunch.
- I can't.

547
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:38,011
You were doing a crossword puzzle,
you used his pen.

548
00:31:38,012 --> 00:31:41,933
No, listen, kid,
I took those balls years ago, Pop,

549
00:31:42,016 --> 00:31:45,061
and now I walk in with this fountain pen
that clinches it.

550
00:31:45,145 --> 00:31:48,273
Don't you understand? I can't face him.
I'll try elsewhere.

551
00:31:48,356 --> 00:31:51,276
- Don't you want to be anything?
- How can I go back?

552
00:31:51,359 --> 00:31:52,693
Pop!

553
00:31:52,694 --> 00:31:55,404
You don't want to be anything,
that what's behind it?

554
00:31:55,405 --> 00:31:59,033
Don't take it that way! You think
it was easy walking into that office?

555
00:31:59,117 --> 00:32:02,162
A team of horses couldn't
have dragged me to Oliver.

556
00:32:02,245 --> 00:32:05,122
- Then why did you go?
- Why did I go?

557
00:32:05,123 --> 00:32:08,960
Why did I go? Dad, look at you.
Look at what's become of you.

558
00:32:09,043 --> 00:32:12,922
- You're gonna go to that lunch.
- I can't. I've got no appointment.

559
00:32:13,047 --> 00:32:15,424
- Are you spiting me?
- Don't take it that way!

560
00:32:15,425 --> 00:32:18,303
You rotten little louse.
Are you spiting me?

561
00:32:18,386 --> 00:32:21,848
Dad. I'm no good.
Can't you see what I am?

562
00:32:21,931 --> 00:32:25,018
You're in a restaurant.
Cut it out, both of you!

563
00:32:25,101 --> 00:32:28,313
- Someone's at the door.
- Hello, girls. Sit down.

564
00:32:28,396 --> 00:32:30,606
Yes, we might as well.
This is Letta.

565
00:32:30,607 --> 00:32:33,443
- What do you drink?
- Letta might not be able to stay.

566
00:32:33,526 --> 00:32:37,696
I gotta get up very early
tomorrow. I've got jury duty.

567
00:32:37,697 --> 00:32:40,783
I'm so excited.
Were you fellas ever on a jury?

568
00:32:40,867 --> 00:32:44,261
No, I've been in front of a jury.

569
00:32:46,180 --> 00:32:49,892
- This is my father.
- Isn't he cute. Sit down with us, Pops.

570
00:32:50,018 --> 00:32:52,227
- Biff, sit him down.
- Come on, sit down.

571
00:32:52,228 --> 00:32:55,690
- Drink us under the table.
- Willy, are you coming?

572
00:32:55,773 --> 00:32:58,191
Willy, I'm waiting.

573
00:32:58,192 --> 00:33:00,402
- Where are you going?
- To open the door.

574
00:33:00,403 --> 00:33:03,155
- What door?
- The washroom. Where is the door?

575
00:33:03,156 --> 00:33:06,091
Just go straight down.

576
00:33:06,784 --> 00:33:10,204
Will you stop laughing. Stop. Shh.

577
00:33:10,288 --> 00:33:12,956
Will you stop!

578
00:33:12,957 --> 00:33:15,059
Shh!

579
00:33:15,084 --> 00:33:17,002
Will you stop!

580
00:33:17,003 --> 00:33:19,588
I think it's sweet you bring your daddy.

581
00:33:19,589 --> 00:33:21,715
Oh, he isn't really your father.

582
00:33:21,716 --> 00:33:24,844
Miss Forsythe, you've just seen
a prince walk by.

583
00:33:25,027 --> 00:33:29,122
A fine troubled prince. A
hard-working, unappreciated prince.

584
00:33:29,223 --> 00:33:31,725
A pal, do you understand,
a good companion.

585
00:33:31,726 --> 00:33:34,578
Always for his boys.

586
00:33:36,522 --> 00:33:39,692
- That's so sweet.
- Girls, we're wasting time here.

587
00:33:39,776 --> 00:33:42,360
What's the programme?
Biff, gather round now.

588
00:33:42,361 --> 00:33:44,154
Where would you like to go?

589
00:33:44,155 --> 00:33:46,799
- You do something for me?
- Me?

590
00:33:47,492 --> 00:33:50,703
- Don't you give a damn for him?
- What are you talking about?

591
00:33:50,787 --> 00:33:53,538
- I'm the one...
- You don't give a damn about him.

592
00:33:53,539 --> 00:33:56,642
Look what I found in the cellar, Hap.

593
00:33:56,667 --> 00:34:00,338
- How can you bear to let that go on?
- Me? Who goes off? Who runs away?

594
00:34:00,421 --> 00:34:03,758
He doesn't mean anything to you.
You could help him, I can't.

595
00:34:03,841 --> 00:34:07,762
Don't you understand what he's gonna do?
He's gonna kill himself.

596
00:34:07,845 --> 00:34:10,097
- Don't you know that?
- Don't yell at me.

597
00:34:10,098 --> 00:34:12,182
Hap, help him.

598
00:34:12,183 --> 00:34:15,478
Help him!
Help me.

599
00:34:15,603 --> 00:34:17,646
Help me!

600
00:34:17,647 --> 00:34:20,874
I can't bear to look in his face.

601
00:34:22,819 --> 00:34:24,528
Biff...

602
00:34:24,529 --> 00:34:27,280
- Biff, where you going?
- What's he so mad about?

603
00:34:27,281 --> 00:34:29,032
We're gonna catch up with him.

604
00:34:29,033 --> 00:34:31,868
- I don't like that temper of his.
- He's overstrung.

605
00:34:31,869 --> 00:34:35,164
- Do you want to tell your father?
- That's not my father, just a guy.

606
00:34:35,248 --> 00:34:39,460
Come on, we're gonna catch up with Biff
and honey, we'll paint this town.

607
00:34:39,544 --> 00:34:43,005
I love those bedroom eyes.

608
00:34:43,089 --> 00:34:48,553
- That's how I knew you were friends.
- Mr Loman! Mr Loman! Mr Loman!

609
00:34:48,636 --> 00:34:51,639
Hey! Mr Loman!

610
00:34:51,764 --> 00:34:53,932
- Willyl
- What?

611
00:34:53,933 --> 00:34:56,142
Oh.

612
00:34:56,143 --> 00:34:58,019
No.

613
00:34:58,020 --> 00:35:01,774
Willy, aren't you gonna answer the door?

614
00:35:01,858 --> 00:35:03,917
Willy...

615
00:35:05,861 --> 00:35:07,696
Willyl

616
00:35:07,697 --> 00:35:10,799
- Arert you gonna answer the door?
- Sure.

617
00:35:13,744 --> 00:35:16,538
Oh.

618
00:35:16,539 --> 00:35:20,868
Someone's at the door, Willy.
Are you gonna answer the door?

619
00:35:21,252 --> 00:35:24,171
He's gonna wake up the whole hotell

620
00:35:25,407 --> 00:35:28,108
I'm not expecting anybody.

621
00:35:28,509 --> 00:35:31,429
Why don't you have another drink, honey?

622
00:35:31,512 --> 00:35:34,807
- Stop being so damn self-centred.
- I'm so Ionely.

623
00:35:34,890 --> 00:35:38,552
You know you ruined me, Willy. From
now on, when you come to the office,

624
00:35:38,653 --> 00:35:41,229
I'll see you
go right through the buyers.

625
00:35:41,230 --> 00:35:44,065
No waiting at my desk anymore.
Willy, you ruined me.

626
00:35:44,066 --> 00:35:46,359
Oh, that's nice of you to say that.

627
00:35:46,360 --> 00:35:48,737
Oh, gee, you're self-centred.

628
00:35:48,738 --> 00:35:50,780
Why so sad?

629
00:35:50,781 --> 00:35:54,327
You're the saddest, self-centredest soul
I ever did see-saw.

630
00:35:54,452 --> 00:35:57,455
Oh, boy, huh? What?

631
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,477
Boy, oh boy, oh boy.

632
00:36:05,004 --> 00:36:08,106
Oh, to be dressing
in the middle of the night.

633
00:36:11,761 --> 00:36:13,678
Arert you gonna answer the door?

634
00:36:13,679 --> 00:36:16,599
They're knocking on the wrong door.

635
00:36:16,682 --> 00:36:19,267
But they're knocking
and hear us talking.

636
00:36:19,268 --> 00:36:21,770
- Maybe the hotel's on fire.
- It's a mistake.

637
00:36:21,771 --> 00:36:24,397
- Tell them to go away.
- There's nobody there.

638
00:36:24,398 --> 00:36:26,274
Willy!

639
00:36:26,275 --> 00:36:30,821
There's somebody standing out there
and it's getting on my nerves.

640
00:36:30,905 --> 00:36:34,075
All right. Stay in the bathroom
and don't come out.

641
00:36:34,158 --> 00:36:37,411
There's a law in Massachusetts,
so don't come out.

642
00:36:37,495 --> 00:36:41,499
It may be the new room clerk.
He looked mean. It's a mistake.

643
00:36:41,582 --> 00:36:44,668
There's no fire.

644
00:36:44,752 --> 00:36:48,297
- Dad. Why didn't you answer?
- Biff.

645
00:36:48,380 --> 00:36:51,300
- What are you doing in Boston?
- Why didn't you answer?

646
00:36:51,425 --> 00:36:54,177
I was knocking for five minutes.
I called you.

647
00:36:54,178 --> 00:36:57,306
I just heard you. I was in the bathroom
and had the door shut.

648
00:36:57,389 --> 00:36:59,849
Did anything happen at home, huh?

649
00:36:59,850 --> 00:37:02,435
- Dad, I let you down.
- Excuse me?

650
00:37:02,436 --> 00:37:05,606
Biffo, what's this about?
Come on, let's go get you a malt.

651
00:37:05,731 --> 00:37:08,567
Dad, I...

652
00:37:08,651 --> 00:37:13,179
- I flunked math. - Not for the term? -
I haven't got enough credits to graduate.

653
00:37:13,280 --> 00:37:17,284
- Bernard wouldn't give you the answers?
- He did. He tried. I only got a 61.

654
00:37:17,368 --> 00:37:21,038
They wouldn't give you four points?
Birnbaum refused absolutely.

655
00:37:21,122 --> 00:37:23,999
I begged him to give me those points
but he won't listen.

656
00:37:24,083 --> 00:37:27,044
You gotta talk to him.
Dad, before they close the school.

657
00:37:27,128 --> 00:37:30,923
'Cause if he saw the kind of man you are
and you talked to him in your way,

658
00:37:31,048 --> 00:37:33,633
I'm sure he'd come through for me, Pop.

659
00:37:33,634 --> 00:37:37,179
The class came right before practice,
so I didn't go enough.

660
00:37:37,304 --> 00:37:40,474
Would you talk to him?
He'd like you, the way you can talk.

661
00:37:40,558 --> 00:37:43,309
- I'm gonna drive right back.
- Dad, good work.

662
00:37:43,310 --> 00:37:46,397
- I'm sure he'll change it.
- Tell the clerk I'm checking out.

663
00:37:46,480 --> 00:37:49,232
Go right down.

664
00:37:49,233 --> 00:37:52,486
The reason he hates me
is one day he was late for class,

665
00:37:52,570 --> 00:37:55,196
so I got up at the blackboard
and imitated him.

666
00:37:55,197 --> 00:37:57,907
- Crossed my eyes, talked with a lisp.
- You did?

667
00:37:57,908 --> 00:37:59,993
- Yeah.
- The kids like it?

668
00:37:59,994 --> 00:38:03,163
- They nearly died laughing.
- Yeah, what did you do?

669
00:38:03,247 --> 00:38:07,793
The square root of 63 is...

670
00:38:07,877 --> 00:38:09,711
In the middle of it he walks in.

671
00:38:09,712 --> 00:38:13,215
He walked in! All right.

672
00:38:15,551 --> 00:38:17,969
- Is somebody in there?
- That was next door.

673
00:38:17,970 --> 00:38:21,974
- Somebody got in your bathroom.
- In the next room there's a party.

674
00:38:22,057 --> 00:38:24,809
Can I come in?

675
00:38:24,810 --> 00:38:28,230
There's something in the bathtub, Willy,
and it's moving.

676
00:38:50,002 --> 00:38:53,172
Uh, you better go back to your room now.

677
00:38:53,255 --> 00:38:56,884
They must be finished painting by now.

678
00:38:56,967 --> 00:39:00,262
See, they're painting her room,
